.TH AARU5 1 "@DATE@" "Aaru @VERSION@" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
aaru5 \- Aaru 5.x stable data-preservation CLI (MPF-compatible)
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B aaru5
.RI [ options ...]
.RI [ command ]
.RI [ command-options ...]
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B Aaru
is a cross-platform data preservation suite. It dumps optical and
removable media (CD, DVD, HD-DVD, Blu-ray, UMD, GameCube/Wii optical,
floppy disks, magneto-optical) to byte-perfect images, decodes their
filesystems, validates checksums, and produces metadata in the CICM
format used by preservation projects.
.PP
.B aaru5
is the stable
.B 5.4.x
release, installed under its own name so it can sit next to the rolling
.BR aaru (1)
(v6 alpha) package. It is the Aaru series that
.B MPF
(the Media Preservation Frontend) drives for floppy and optical dumping;
the v6 alpha has an incompatible command interface and does not work in
MPF. In MPF, set the Aaru executable path to
.IR /usr/bin/aaru5 .
.SH OPTIONS
These global options precede the command name.
.TP
.BR \-v ", " \-\-verbose
Show verbose output.
.TP
.BR \-d ", " \-\-debug
Show debug output from plugins.
.TP
.B \-\-pause
Pause before exiting.
.TP
.B \-\-version
Show version information and exit.
.TP
.BR \-? ", " \-h ", " \-\-help
Show help and usage information. Append it to any command
.RB ( "aaru5 \fICOMMAND\fB \-\-help" )
for that command's own options and sub-commands.
.SH COMMANDS
.TP
.BR database ", " db
Manage the device and statistics database.
.TP
.BR dev ", " device
Talk to devices (dump, scan, report, list).
.TP
.BR fi ", " filesystem ", " fs
Manage filesystems (info, list, extract, options).
.TP
.BR i ", " image
Manage images (info, verify, checksum, convert, entropy, decode, print).
.TP
.BR m ", " media
Manage media inserted in devices (dump, info, scan).
.TP
.B configure
Configure user settings and statistics (interactive).
.TP
.B formats
List all supported disc images, partition schemes and filesystems.
.TP
.B list\-encodings
List all supported text encodings and code pages.
.TP
.B list\-namespaces
List all namespaces supported by read-only filesystems.
.TP
.B remote
Test the connection to an Aaru Remote Server
.RI ( host
argument).
.PP
Each command has its own sub-commands and options; run
.B aaru5 \fICOMMAND\fB \-\-help
for the full, version-exact reference from the installed binary.
.SH DRIVE ACCESS
.B aaru5
ships with the
.B cap_sys_rawio
file capability set, so vendor SCSI passthrough commands (optical
dumping) work without sudo.
.PP
The invoking user still needs read/write access to the device node
.RB ( /dev/sr* ,
.BR /dev/sg* ,
removable USB or floppy nodes). On a desktop session at the local seat
this is granted automatically via systemd-logind's
.B uaccess
ACL. For headless use (SSH, cron, systemd
.BR \-\-user ,
NFS-mounted device nodes) add the user to the
.B cdrom
group:
.PP
.RS
.EX
sudo usermod -aG cdrom $USER
newgrp cdrom
.EE
.RE
.PP
USB floppy drives enumerate as
.B root:disk
SCSI block devices
.RB ( /dev/sd* )
and logind does not apply a
.B uaccess
ACL to block devices; dumping one without root needs a udev rule that
grants the node to a group the user is in (shipped by the MPF packages,
not by Aaru itself).
.SH FILES
.TP
.I /usr/bin/aaru5
Symlink to the real binary; the kernel follows it for
.B cap_sys_rawio
inheritance on exec.
.TP
.I /usr/lib64/aaru5/
Real NativeAOT binary
.RI ( aaru )
and its bundled native SQLite provider
.RI ( libe_sqlite3.so ).
.TP
.I ~/.config/Aaru.xml
Per-user settings written by
.BR "aaru5 configure" .
.TP
.I ~/.local/share/Aaru/
Per-user device/media database, statistics and device reports.
.SH NOTES
On first launch Aaru builds its local database and, until
.B aaru5 configure
has been answered once, prints an EU GDPR data-sharing notice and asks
whether to enable copy-protected-media decryption. Run
.B aaru5 configure
once interactively (or opt out) to silence it.
.PP
Aaru derives its config and data paths from the application name, not the
launcher name, so
.B aaru5
reads
.I ~/.config/Aaru.xml
and
.I ~/.local/share/Aaru/
\(em the same locations a standalone
.BR aaru (1)
(v6) install uses. The settings files differ by extension (v6 uses
.IR Aaru.json ),
but the database directory is shared; if you run both as the same user
and hit a schema mismatch, point one of them at a private
.B HOME
or
.B XDG_DATA_HOME .
.PP
This manpage is maintained by hand as part of the Fedora packaging;
upstream provides none. The command overview above is a summary \(em the
authoritative, version-exact reference is the binary's own
.B \-\-help
output.
